<div id="review_4407713146" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4407713146" />
    <a title="Anushka J" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/133636102-anushka-j"><img alt="Anushka J" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4407713146?book_show_action=true">Dec 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anushka J" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anushka J" href="/user/show/133636102-anushka-j">Anushka J</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4407713146" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7432791547065921065">The way I read this while studying for the MCAT ... I was constantly wondering what I was getting myself into. I loved the note in the beginning that clarified that this book isn&apos;t for doctors, it&apos;s for their family and friends to understand what they&apos;re going to, which completely held up. It was blunt, mostly depressing, scary, and very honest. It made me tired just reading it sometimes. Even though it might sound boring (just people talking about their day for 400 pages and how much they hate </span>
  <span id="freeText7432791547065921065" style="display:none">The way I read this while studying for the MCAT ... I was constantly wondering what I was getting myself into. I loved the note in the beginning that clarified that this book isn't for doctors, it's for their family and friends to understand what they're going to, which completely held up. It was blunt, mostly depressing, scary, and very honest. It made me tired just reading it sometimes. Even though it might sound boring (just people talking about their day for 400 pages and how much they hate their lives) I really started rooting for the three interns and just being genuinely curious to see how their months went. A couple of their voice recordings were genuinely funny, and there was quite a bit of distinctive voice (literally) from each intern, which kept it light enough. It's a simple read, but it does exactly what it was meant to.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7432791547065921065" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


